9 Module Name:
10 
11  FileLock.c
12 
13 Abstract:
14 
15  The file lock package provides a set of routines that allow the
16  caller to handle byte range file lock requests. A variable of
17  type FILE_LOCK is needed for every file with byte range locking.
18  The package provides routines to set and clear locks, and to
19  test for read or write access to a file with byte range locks.
20 
21  The main idea of the package is to have the file system initialize
22  a FILE_LOCK variable for every data file as its opened, and then
23  to simply call a file lock processing routine to handle all IRP's
24  with a major function code of LOCK_CONTROL. The package is responsible
25  for keeping track of locks and for completing the LOCK_CONTROL IRPS.
26  When processing a read or write request the file system can then call
27  two query routines to check for access.
28 
29  Most of the code for processing IRPS and checking for access use
30  paged pool and can encounter a page fault, therefore the check routines
31  cannot be called at DPC level. To help servers that do call the file
32  system to do read/write operations at DPC level there is a additional
33  routine that simply checks for the existence of a lock on a file and
34  can be run at DPC level.
35 
36  Concurrent access to the FILE_LOCK variable must be controlled by the
37  caller.
38 
39  The functions provided in this package are as follows:
40 
41  o FsRtlInitializeFileLock - Initialize a new FILE_LOCK structure.
42 
43  o FsRtlUninitializeFileLock - Uninitialize an existing FILE_LOCK
44  structure.
45 
46  o FsRtlProcessFileLock - Process an IRP whose major function code
47  is LOCK_CONTROL.
48 
49  o FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess - Check for read access to a range
50  of bytes in a file given an IRP.
51 
52  o FsRtlCheckLockForWriteAccess - Check for write access to a range
53  of bytes in a file given an IRP.
54 
55  o FsRtlAreThereCurrentFileLocks - Check if there are any locks
56  currently assigned to a file.
57 
58  o FsRtlGetNextFileLock - This procedure enumerates the current locks
59  of a file lock variable.
60 
61  o FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead - Check for read access to a range of
62  bytes in a file given separate parameters.
63 
64  o FsRtlFastCheckLockForWrite - Check for write access to a range of
65  bytes in a file given separate parameters.
66 
67  o FsRtlFastLock - A fast non-Irp based way to get a lock
68 
69  o FsRtlFastUnlockSingle - A fast non-Irp based way to release a single
70  lock
71 
72  o FsRtlFastUnlockAll - A fast non-Irp based way to release all locks
73  held by a file object.
74 
75  o FsRtlFastUnlockAllByKey - A fast non-Irp based way to release all
76  locks held by a file object that match a key.
77 
78 --*/

150 /*++
151 
152  Some of the decisions made regarding the internal datastructures may not be clear,
153  so I should discuss the evolution of this design.
154 
155  The original file lock implementation was a single linked list, extended in the MP
156  case to a set of linked lists which each held locks in page-aligned segments of the
157  file. If locks spilled over these page-aligned segments the code fell back to the
158  UP single linked list. There are clearly performance implications with substantial
159  usage of file locks, since these are mandatory locks.
160 
161  This implementation goes for O(lgn) search performance by using splay trees. In order to
162  apply simple trees to this problem no node of the tree can overlap, so since shared
163  locks can in fact overlap something must be done. The solution used here is to have
164  a meta-structure contain all locks which do overlap and have the tree operations
165  split and merge these nodes of (potentially) multiple locks. This is the LOCKTREE_NODE.
166  It should be noted that the worst case add/delete lock times are still linear.
167 
168  Exclusive locks pose a problem because of an asymmetry in the semantics of applying
169  locks to a file. If a process applies a shared lock to a section of a file, no application
170  of an exclusive lock to bytes in that section can succeed. However, if a process
171  applies an exclusive lock, that same process can get a shared lock as well. This
172  behavior conflicts with the mergeable node since by applying locks in a given order
173  we can get a node to have many shared locks and "rogue" exclusive locks which are
174  hidden except to a linear search, which is what we're designing out. So exclusive locks
175  must be separated from the shared locks. This is the reason we have two lock trees.
176 
177  Since we have two lock trees, the average case search is now O(lgm + lgn) for m exclusive
178  and n shared. Also, since no exclusive locks can ever overlap each other it is now
179  unreasonable to have them use LOCKTREE_NODES - this would impose a memory penalty on code
180  which was weighted toward exclusive locks. This means that the exclusive locks should
181  be wired into the splay tree directly. So we need an RTL_SPLAY_LINKS, but this is 64 bits
182  bigger than the SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY which shared locks need (to be threaded off of a
183  LOCKTREE_NODE), which dictates separate shared and exclusive lock structures to avoid
184  penalizing code which was weighted toward shared locks by having that wasted 64 bits per
185  lock. Hence EX_LOCK and SH_LOCK (they actually occupy different pool block sizes).
186 
187  Zero length locks are a bizarre creation, and there is some errata relating to them. It
188  used to be the case that zero length locks would be granted without exception. This is
189  flat out bogus, and has been changed (NT 4.0). They are now subject to failure if they
190  occupy a point interior to a lock of a type that can cause an access failure. A particular
191  case that was previously allowed was a zero length exclusive lock interior to another
192  exclusive lock.
193 
194  Zero length locks cannot conflict with zero length locks. This is the subject of some
195  special code throughout the module. Note especially that zero length exclusive locks can
196  "overlap". Zero length locks also cannot conflict at the starting byte and ending byte of a
197  range - they are points on the line.
198 
199 --*/

201 typedef struct _LOCKTREE_NODE {
202 
203  //
204  // List of locks under this node
205  //
206 
207  SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY Locks;
208 
209  //
210  // Flag whether this node is holey as a result of a failed allocation
211  // during a node split. During deletion of shared locks, we may
212  // discover that the locks in the node no longer have total overlap
213  // but cannot allocate resources to create the new nodes in the tree.
214  //
215  // Any insert into the region occupied by a holey node will finish by
216  // trying to split a holey node up. Any split or access check in a
217  // holey node must completely traverse the locks at the node.
218  //
219 
220  BOOLEAN HoleyNode;
221 
222  //
223  // Maximum byte offset affected by locks in this node.
224  // Note: minimum offset is the starting offset of the
225  // first lock at this node.
226  //
227 
228  ULONGLONG Extent;
229 
230  //
231  // Splay tree links to parent, lock groups strictly less than
232  // and lock groups strictly greater than locks in this node.
233  //
234 
235  RTL_SPLAY_LINKS Links;
236 
237  //
238  // Last lock in the list (useful for node collapse under insert)
239  //
240 
241  SINGLE_LIST_ENTRY Tail;
242 
243 } LOCKTREE_NODE, *PLOCKTREE_NODE;

504 //
505 // Generic way to complete a lock IRP. We like to treat this as an overloaded
506 // function so it can be used with LOCK_INFO, FILE_LOCK and WAITING_LOCK
507 // structures, as appropriate using paged/nonpaged pool to discover the completion
508 // routine.
509 //
510 
511 #define FsRtlCompleteLockIrp( A, B, C, D, E, F ) \
512  FsRtlCompleteLockIrpReal( (A)->CompleteLockIrpRoutine, \
513  B, \
514  C, \
515  D, \
516  E, \
517  F )
518 
519 INLINE
520 VOID
521 FsRtlCompleteLockIrpReal (
522  IN PCOMPLETE_LOCK_IRP_ROUTINE CompleteLockIrpRoutine,
523  IN PVOID Context,
524  IN PIRP Irp,
525  IN NTSTATUS Status,
526  IN PNTSTATUS NewStatus,
527  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
528  )
529 {
530  //
531  // This fools the compiler into generating the Status only once
532  // if it is calculated from an expression.
533  //
534 
535  NTSTATUS LocalStatus = Status;
536 
537  if (CompleteLockIrpRoutine != NULL) {
538 
539  if (FileObject != NULL) {
540 
541  FileObject->LastLock = NULL;
542  }
543 
544  Irp->IoStatus.Status = LocalStatus;
545  *NewStatus = CompleteLockIrpRoutine( Context, Irp );
546 
547  } else {
548 
549  FsRtlCompleteRequest( Irp, LocalStatus );
550  *NewStatus = LocalStatus;
551  }
552 }

793  KeInitializeSpinLock( &FsRtlFileLockCancelCollideLock );
794  FsRtlFileLockCancelCollideList.Next = NULL;
795 }

798 VOID
799 FsRtlInitializeFileLock (
800  __in PFILE_LOCK FileLock,
801  __in_opt PCOMPLETE_LOCK_IRP_ROUTINE CompleteLockIrpRoutine,
802  __in_opt PUNLOCK_ROUTINE UnlockRoutine
803  )
804 
805 /*++
806 
807 Routine Description:
808 
809  This routine initializes a new FILE_LOCK structure. The caller must
810  supply the memory for the structure. This call must precede all other
811  calls that utilize the FILE_LOCK variable.
812 
813 Arguments:
814 
815  FileLock - Supplies a pointer to the FILE_LOCK structure to
816  initialize.
817 
818  CompleteLockIrpRoutine - Optionally supplies an alternate routine to
819  call for completing IRPs. FsRtlProcessFileLock by default will
820  call IoCompleteRequest to finish up an IRP; however if the caller
821  want to process the completion itself then it needs to specify
822  a completion routine here. This routine will then be called in
823  place of IoCompleteRequest.
824 
825  UnlockRoutine - Optionally supplies a routine to call when removing
826  a lock.
827 
828 Return Value:
829 
830  None.
831 
832 --*/
833 
834 {
835  DebugTrace(+1, Dbg, "FsRtlInitializeFileLock, FileLock = %08lx\n", FileLock);
836 
837  //
838  // Clear non-paged pool pointer
839  //
840 
841  FileLock->LockInformation = NULL;
842  FileLock->CompleteLockIrpRoutine = CompleteLockIrpRoutine;
843  FileLock->UnlockRoutine = UnlockRoutine;
844 
845  FileLock->FastIoIsQuestionable = FALSE;
846 
847  //
848  // and return to our caller
849  //
850 
851  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlInitializeFileLock -> VOID\n", 0 );
852 
853  return;
854 }
855 
856 
857 BOOLEAN
858 FsRtlPrivateInitializeFileLock (
859  IN PFILE_LOCK FileLock,
860  IN BOOLEAN ViaFastCall
861  )
862 /*++
863 
864 Routine Description:
865 
866  This routine initializes a new LOCK_INFO structure in non-paged
867  pool for the FILE_LOCK. This routines only occurs once for a given
868  FILE_LOCK and it only occurs if any locks are applied to that file.
869 
870 Arguments:
871 
872  FileLock - Supplies a pointer to the FILE_LOCK structure to
873  initialize.
874 
875  ViaFastCall - Indicates if we are being invoked via a fast call or
876  via the slow irp based method.
877 
878 Return Value:
879 
880  TRUE - If LockInfo structure was allocated and initialized
881 
882 --*/
883 {
884  PLOCK_INFO LockInfo;
885  BOOLEAN Results = FALSE;
886 
887  KeAcquireGuardedMutex( &FsRtlCreateLockInfo );
888 
889  try {
890 
891  if (FileLock->LockInformation != NULL) {
892 
893  //
894  // Structure is already allocated, just return
895  //
896 
897  try_return( Results = TRUE );
898  }
899 
900  //
901  // Allocate pool for lock structures. If we fail then we will either return false or
902  // raise based on if we know the caller has an try-except to handle a raise.
903  //
904 
905  LockInfo = FsRtlAllocateLockInfo();
906 
907  if (LockInfo == NULL) {
908 
909  if (ViaFastCall) {
910 
911  try_return( Results = FALSE );
912 
913  } else {
914 
915  ExRaiseStatus( STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES );
916  }
917  }
918 
919  //
920  // Allocate and initialize the waiting lock queue
921  // spinlock, and initialize the queues
922  //
923 
924  LockInfo->LowestLockOffset = 0xffffffff;
925 
926  KeInitializeSpinLock( &LockInfo->LockQueue.QueueSpinLock );
927  LockInfo->LockQueue.SharedLockTree = NULL;
928  LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree = NULL;
929  LockInfo->LockQueue.WaitingLocks.Next = NULL;
930  LockInfo->LockQueue.WaitingLocksTail.Next = NULL;
931 
932  //
933  // Copy Irp & Unlock routines from pageable FileLock structure
934  // to non-pageable LockInfo structure
935  //
936 
937  LockInfo->CompleteLockIrpRoutine = FileLock->CompleteLockIrpRoutine;
938  LockInfo->UnlockRoutine = FileLock->UnlockRoutine;
939 
940  //
941  // Clear continuation info for enum routine
942  //
943 
944  FileLock->LastReturnedLockInfo.FileObject = NULL;
945  FileLock->LastReturnedLock = NULL;
946 
947  //
948  // Link LockInfo into FileLock
949  //
950 
951  FileLock->LockInformation = (PVOID) LockInfo;
952  Results = TRUE;
953 
954  try_exit: NOTHING;
955  } finally {
956 
957  KeReleaseGuardedMutex( &FsRtlCreateLockInfo );
958  }
959 
960  return Results;
961 }
962 
963 
964 VOID
965 FsRtlUninitializeFileLock (
966  __in PFILE_LOCK FileLock
967  )
968 
969 /*++
970 
971 Routine Description:
972 
973  This routine uninitializes a FILE_LOCK structure. After calling this
974  routine the File lock must be reinitialized before being used again.
975 
976  This routine will free all files locks and completes any outstanding
977  lock requests as a result of cleaning itself up.
978 
979 Arguments:
980 
981  FileLock - Supplies a pointer to the FILE_LOCK structure being
982  decommissioned.
983 
984 Return Value:
985 
986  None.
987 
988 --*/
989 
990 {
991  PLOCK_INFO LockInfo;
992  PSH_LOCK ShLock;
993  PEX_LOCK ExLock;
994  PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY Link;
995  PWAITING_LOCK WaitingLock;
996  PLOCKTREE_NODE LockTreeNode;
997  PIRP Irp;
998  NTSTATUS NewStatus;
999  KIRQL OldIrql;
1000 
1001  DebugTrace(+1, Dbg, "FsRtlUninitializeFileLock, FileLock = %08lx\n", FileLock);
1002 
1003  if ((LockInfo = (PLOCK_INFO) FileLock->LockInformation) == NULL) {
1004  return ;
1005  }
1006 
1007  //
1008  // Lock vs. cancels and lock the queue.
1009  //
1010 
1011  FsRtlAcquireCancelCollide( &OldIrql );
1012  FsRtlAcquireLockQueueAtDpc( &LockInfo->LockQueue );
1013 
1014  //
1015  // Free lock trees
1016  //
1017 
1018  while (LockInfo->LockQueue.SharedLockTree != NULL) {
1019 
1020  LockTreeNode = CONTAINING_RECORD(LockInfo->LockQueue.SharedLockTree, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links);
1021 
1022  //
1023  // Remove all locks associated with the root node
1024  //
1025 
1026  while (LockTreeNode->Locks.Next != NULL) {
1027  Link = PopEntryList (&LockTreeNode->Locks);
1028  ShLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, SH_LOCK, Link );
1029 
1030  FsRtlFreeSharedLock(ShLock);
1031  }
1032 
1033  //
1034  // Slice off the root node of the tree
1035  //
1036 
1037  RtlDeleteNoSplay(&LockTreeNode->Links, &LockInfo->LockQueue.SharedLockTree);
1038 
1039  FsRtlFreeLockTreeNode(LockTreeNode);
1040  }
1041 
1042  while (LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree != NULL) {
1043 
1044  ExLock = CONTAINING_RECORD(LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree, EX_LOCK, Links);
1045 
1046  RtlDeleteNoSplay(&ExLock->Links, &LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree);
1047 
1048  FsRtlFreeExclusiveLock(ExLock);
1049  }
1050 
1051  //
1052  // Free WaitingLockQueue.
1053  //
1054  // This will be incredibly rare, requiring a cancel to be pending in an async thread
1055  // while cleanup/close occurs in the owning filesystem, triggering teardown.
1056  //
1057 
1058  while (LockInfo->LockQueue.WaitingLocks.Next != NULL) {
1059 
1060  Link = PopEntryList( &LockInfo->LockQueue.WaitingLocks );
1061  WaitingLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, WAITING_LOCK, Link );
1062 
1063  Irp = WaitingLock->Irp;
1064 
1065  //
1066  // To complete an irp in the waiting queue we need to
1067  // void the cancel routine (protected by a spinlock so
1068  // we can know that we beat cancellation) before
1069  // we completing the irp.
1070  //
1071 
1072  FsRtlReleaseLockQueueFromDpc( &LockInfo->LockQueue );
1073 
1074  IoAcquireCancelSpinLock( &Irp->CancelIrql );
1075  IoSetCancelRoutine( Irp, NULL );
1076 
1077  //
1078  // If it got cancelled, the cancel routine is now waiting on the other
1079  // side of the cancel collide for us to push it onto the collide list.
1080  // It'll get the IRP there as opposed to the shortly-to-be-axed lock
1081  // structure.
1082  //
1083 
1084  if (Irp->Cancel) {
1085 
1086  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( Irp->CancelIrql );
1087  PushEntryList( &FsRtlFileLockCancelCollideList,
1088  &WaitingLock->Link );
1089  Irp = NULL;
1090 
1091  } else {
1092 
1093  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( Irp->CancelIrql );
1094  }
1095 
1096  //
1097  // If we got the ownership of the IRP, release the collide and complete
1098  // it, otherwise spin back around for more.
1099  //
1100 
1101  if (Irp) {
1102 
1103  FsRtlReleaseCancelCollide( OldIrql );
1104 
1105  Irp->IoStatus.Information = 0;
1106 
1107  FsRtlCompleteLockIrp(
1108  LockInfo,
1109  WaitingLock->Context,
1110  Irp,
1111  STATUS_RANGE_NOT_LOCKED,
1112  &NewStatus,
1113  NULL );
1114 
1115  FsRtlFreeWaitingLock( WaitingLock );
1116 
1117  FsRtlAcquireCancelCollide( &OldIrql );
1118  }
1119 
1120  FsRtlAcquireLockQueueAtDpc( &LockInfo->LockQueue );
1121  }
1122 
1123  //
1124  // Release locks and free pool used to track the lock info on this file.
1125  //
1126 
1127  FsRtlReleaseLockQueueFromDpc( &LockInfo->LockQueue );
1128  FsRtlReleaseCancelCollide( OldIrql );
1129  FsRtlFreeLockInfo( LockInfo );
1130 
1131  //
1132  // Unlink LockInfo from FileLock
1133  //
1134 
1135  FileLock->LockInformation = NULL;
1136 
1137  //
1138  // And return to our caller
1139  //
1140 
1141  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlUninitializeFileLock -> VOID\n", 0 );
1142  return;
1143 }

1176 
1177 NTSTATUS
1178 FsRtlProcessFileLock (
1179  __in PFILE_LOCK FileLock,
1180  __in PIRP Irp,
1181  __in_opt PVOID Context
1182  )
1183 
1184 /*++
1185 
1186 Routine Description:
1187 
1188  This routine processes a file lock IRP it does either a lock request,
1189  or an unlock request. It also completes the IRP. Once called the user
1190  (i.e., File System) has relinquished control of the input IRP.
1191 
1192  If pool is not available to store the information this routine will raise a
1193  status value indicating insufficient resources.
1194 
1195 Arguments:
1196 
1197  FileLock - Supplies the File lock being modified/queried.
1198 
1199  Irp - Supplies the Irp being processed.
1200 
1201  Context - Optionally supplies a context to use when calling the user
1202  alternate IRP completion routine.
1203 
1204 Return Value:
1205 
1206  NTSTATUS - The return status for the operation.
1207 
1208 --*/
1209 
1210 {
1211  PIO_STACK_LOCATION IrpSp;
1212 
1213  IO_STATUS_BLOCK Iosb;
1214  NTSTATUS Status;
1215  LARGE_INTEGER ByteOffset;
1216 
1217  DebugTrace(+1, Dbg, "FsRtlProcessFileLock, FileLock = %08lx\n", FileLock);
1218 
1219  Iosb.Information = 0;
1220 
1221  //
1222  // Get a pointer to the current Irp stack location and assert that
1223  // the major function code is for a lock operation
1224  //
1225 
1226  IrpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp );
1227 
1228  ASSERT( IrpSp->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_LOCK_CONTROL );
1229 
1230  //
1231  // Now process the different minor lock operations
1232  //
1233 
1234  switch (IrpSp->MinorFunction) {
1235 
1236  case IRP_MN_LOCK:
1237 
1238  ByteOffset = IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.ByteOffset;
1239 
1240  (VOID) FsRtlPrivateLock( FileLock,
1241  IrpSp->FileObject,
1242  &ByteOffset,
1243  IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Length,
1244  IoGetRequestorProcess(Irp),
1245  IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Key,
1246  BooleanFlagOn(IrpSp->Flags, SL_FAIL_IMMEDIATELY),
1247  BooleanFlagOn(IrpSp->Flags, SL_EXCLUSIVE_LOCK),
1248  &Iosb,
1249  Irp,
1250  Context,
1251  FALSE );
1252 
1253  break;
1254 
1255  case IRP_MN_UNLOCK_SINGLE:
1256 
1257  ByteOffset = IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.ByteOffset;
1258 
1259  Iosb.Status = FsRtlFastUnlockSingle( FileLock,
1260  IrpSp->FileObject,
1261  &ByteOffset,
1262  IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Length,
1263  IoGetRequestorProcess(Irp),
1264  IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Key,
1265  Context,
1266  FALSE );
1267 
1268  FsRtlCompleteLockIrp( FileLock, Context, Irp, Iosb.Status, &Status, NULL );
1269  break;
1270 
1271  case IRP_MN_UNLOCK_ALL:
1272 
1273  Iosb.Status = FsRtlFastUnlockAll( FileLock,
1274  IrpSp->FileObject,
1275  IoGetRequestorProcess(Irp),
1276  Context );
1277 
1278  FsRtlCompleteLockIrp( FileLock, Context, Irp, Iosb.Status, &Status, NULL );
1279  break;
1280 
1281  case IRP_MN_UNLOCK_ALL_BY_KEY:
1282 
1283  Iosb.Status = FsRtlFastUnlockAllByKey( FileLock,
1284  IrpSp->FileObject,
1285  IoGetRequestorProcess(Irp),
1286  IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Key,
1287  Context );
1288 
1289  FsRtlCompleteLockIrp( FileLock, Context, Irp, Iosb.Status, &Status, NULL );
1290  break;
1291 
1292  default:
1293 
1294  //
1295  // For all other minor function codes we say they're invalid and
1296  // complete the request. Note that the IRP has not been marked
1297  // pending so this error will be returned directly to the caller.
1298  //
1299 
1300  DebugTrace(0, 1, "Invalid LockFile Minor Function Code %08lx\n", IrpSp->MinorFunction);
1301 
1302 
1303  FsRtlCompleteRequest( Irp, STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST );
1304 
1305  Iosb.Status = STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST;
1306  break;
1307  }
1308 
1309  //
1310  // And return to our caller
1311  //
1312 
1313  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlProcessFileLock -> %08lx\n", Iosb.Status);
1314 
1315  return Iosb.Status;
1316 }

1319 BOOLEAN
1320 FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess (
1321  __in PFILE_LOCK FileLock,
1322  __in PIRP Irp
1323  )
1324 
1325 /*++
1326 
1327 Routine Description:
1328 
1329  This routine checks to see if the caller has read access to the
1330  range indicated in the IRP due to file locks. This call does not
1331  complete the Irp it only uses it to get the lock information and read
1332  information. The IRP must be for a read operation.
1333 
1334 Arguments:
1335 
1336  FileLock - Supplies the File Lock to check.
1337 
1338  Irp - Supplies the Irp being processed.
1339 
1340 Return Value:
1341 
1342  BOOLEAN - TRUE if the indicated user/request has read access to the
1343  entire specified byte range, and FALSE otherwise
1344 
1345 --*/
1346 
1347 {
1348  BOOLEAN Result;
1349 
1350  PIO_STACK_LOCATION IrpSp;
1351 
1352  PLOCK_INFO LockInfo;
1353  LARGE_INTEGER StartingByte;
1354  LARGE_INTEGER Length;
1355  ULONG Key;
1356  PFILE_OBJECT FileObject;
1357  PVOID ProcessId;
1358  LARGE_INTEGER BeyondLastByte;
1359 
1360  DebugTrace(+1, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess, FileLock = %08lx\n", FileLock);
1361 
1362  if ((LockInfo = (PLOCK_INFO) FileLock->LockInformation) == NULL) {
1363  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess (No current lock info) -> TRUE\n", 0);
1364  return TRUE;
1365  }
1366 
1367  //
1368  // Do a really fast test to see if there are any exclusive locks to start with
1369  //
1370 
1371  if (LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree == NULL) {
1372  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess (No current locks) -> TRUE\n", 0);
1373  return TRUE;
1374  }
1375 
1376  //
1377  // Get the read offset and compare it to the lowest existing lock.
1378  //
1379 
1380  IrpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp );
1381 
1382  StartingByte = IrpSp->Parameters.Read.ByteOffset;
1383  Length.QuadPart = (ULONGLONG)IrpSp->Parameters.Read.Length;
1384 
1385  BeyondLastByte.QuadPart = (ULONGLONG)StartingByte.QuadPart + Length.LowPart;
1386  if ( (ULONGLONG)BeyondLastByte.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)LockInfo->LowestLockOffset ) {
1387  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess (Below lowest lock) -> TRUE\n", 0);
1388  return TRUE;
1389  }
1390 
1391  //
1392  // Get remaining parameters.
1393  //
1394 
1395  Key = IrpSp->Parameters.Read.Key;
1396  FileObject = IrpSp->FileObject;
1397  ProcessId = IoGetRequestorProcess( Irp );
1398 
1399  //
1400  // Call our private work routine to do the real check
1401  //
1402 
1403  Result = FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead( FileLock,
1404  &StartingByte,
1405  &Length,
1406  Key,
1407  FileObject,
1408  ProcessId );
1409 
1410  //
1411  // And return to our caller
1412  //
1413 
1414  DebugTrace(-1, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckLockForReadAccess -> %08lx\n", Result);
1415 
1416  return Result;
1417 }

1520 
1521 PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS
1522 FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingSharedNode (
1523  IN PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Tree,
1524  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingByte,
1525  IN PLARGE_INTEGER EndingByte,
1526  IN OUT PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS *LastEdgeNode,
1527  IN OUT PBOOLEAN GreaterThan
1528  )
1529 /*++
1530 
1531 Routine Description:
1532 
1533  This routine returns the first node in the shared lock tree which
1534  overlaps with the range given. No nodes given by RtlRealPredecessor()
1535  on the result overlap the range.
1536 
1537 Arguments:
1538 
1539  Tree - supplies the splay links of the root node of the shared tree
1540  to search
1541 
1542  StartingByte - supplies the first byte offset of the range to check
1543 
1544  EndingByte - supplies the last byte offset of the range to check
1545 
1546  LastEdgeNode - optional, will be set to the last node searched in the
1547  not including returned node (presumably where a new node will
1548  be inserted if return is NULL).
1549 
1550  GreaterThan - optional, set according to whether LastEdgeNode is covering
1551  a range greater than the queried range. !GreaterThan == LessThan, since
1552  we would have returned this node in the "Equals" (overlap) case.
1553 
1554 Return Value:
1555 
1556  The splay links of the node, if such a node exists, NULL otherwise
1557 
1558 --*/
1559 {
1560  PLOCKTREE_NODE Node = NULL, LastOverlapNode;
1561  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS SplayLinks;
1562  PSH_LOCK Lock;
1563 
1564  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = NULL;
1565  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = FALSE;
1566 
1567  LastOverlapNode = NULL;
1568  SplayLinks = Tree;
1569 
1570  while (SplayLinks) {
1571 
1572  Node = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links );
1573 
1574  //
1575  // Pull up the first lock on the chain at this node to check
1576  // the starting byte offset of locks at this node
1577  //
1578 
1579  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Node->Locks.Next, SH_LOCK, Link );
1580 
1581  //
1582  // We may have to go right in the tree if this lock covers a range before the start of this
1583  // range we are looking for overlap on or this lock is [0, 0). This is important since a lock
1584  // on [0, 0) will look like the extent is from [0, ~0], which is the only case where the zero
1585  // length lock relation of End < Start does not hold.
1586  //
1587 
1588  if (Node->Extent < (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart ||
1589  (Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == 0 && Lock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart == 0)) {
1590 
1591  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)EndingByte->QuadPart &&
1592  (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart) {
1593 
1594  //
1595  // The extent of the node is less than the starting position of the
1596  // range we are checking and the first lock on this node is equal to
1597  // the range, which implies that the range and the lock are zero
1598  // length.
1599  //
1600  // This is a zero length lock node and we are searching for zero
1601  // length overlap. This makes multiple zero length shared locks
1602  // occupy the same node, which is a win, but makes application of
1603  // zero length exclusive locks check the length of the overlapping
1604  // lock to see if they really conflict.
1605  //
1606 
1607  break;
1608  }
1609 
1610  //
1611  // All locks at this node are strictly less than this
1612  // byterange, so go right in the tree.
1613  //
1614 
1615  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = SplayLinks;
1616  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = FALSE;
1617 
1618  SplayLinks = RtlRightChild(SplayLinks);
1619  continue;
1620  }
1621 
1622  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)EndingByte->QuadPart) {
1623 
1624  //
1625  // We have an overlap, but we need to see if the byterange starts
1626  // before this node so that there is the guarantee that we start
1627  // the search at the correct point. There may be still be predecessor
1628  // nodes covering the byterange.
1629  //
1630 
1631  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart) {
1632 
1633  //
1634  // This node begins at a byte offset prior to the byterange we
1635  // are checking, so it must be the correct starting position.
1636  //
1637 
1638  break;
1639  }
1640 
1641  //
1642  // Drop a marker at this node so that we can come back if it turns out
1643  // that the left subtree does not cover the range of bytes before this
1644  // node in the byterange.
1645  //
1646 
1647  LastOverlapNode = Node;
1648  }
1649 
1650  //
1651  // It must now be the case that all locks at this node are strictly greater
1652  // than the byterange, or we have the candidate overlap case above,
1653  // so go left in the tree.
1654  //
1655 
1656  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = SplayLinks;
1657  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = TRUE;
1658 
1659  SplayLinks = RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks);
1660  }
1661 
1662  if (SplayLinks == NULL) {
1663 
1664  //
1665  // We hit the edge of the tree. If the LastOverlapNode is set, it means that
1666  // we had kept searching left in the tree for a node that covered the starting
1667  // byte of the byterange, but didn't find it. If it isn't set, we'll do the
1668  // right thing anyway since Node <- NULL.
1669  //
1670 
1671  Node = LastOverlapNode;
1672  }
1673 
1674  if (Node == NULL) {
1675 
1676  //
1677  // No overlapping node existed
1678  //
1679 
1680  return NULL;
1681  }
1682 
1683  //
1684  // Return the splay links of the first overlapping node
1685  //
1686 
1687  return &Node->Links;
1688 }

1691 PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS
1692 FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingExclusiveNode (
1693  IN PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS Tree,
1694  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingByte,
1695  IN PLARGE_INTEGER EndingByte,
1696  IN OUT PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS *LastEdgeNode,
1697  IN OUT PBOOLEAN GreaterThan
1698  )
1699 /*++
1700 
1701 Routine Description:
1702 
1703  This routine returns the first node in the exclusive lock tree which
1704  overlaps with the range given. No nodes given by RtlRealPredecessor()
1705  on the result overlap the range.
1706 
1707 Arguments:
1708 
1709  Tree - supplies the splay links of the root node of the exclusive tree
1710  to search
1711 
1712  StartingByte - supplies the first byte offset of the range to check
1713 
1714  EndingByte - supplies the last byte offset of the range to check
1715 
1716  LastEdgeNode - optional, will be set to the last node searched
1717  not including returned node (presumably where a new node will
1718  be inserted if return is NULL).
1719 
1720  GreaterThan - optional, set according to whether LastEdgeNode is covering
1721  a range greater than the queried range. !GreaterThan == LessThan, since
1722  we would have returned this node in the "Equals" (overlap) case.
1723 
1724 Return Value:
1725 
1726  The splay links of the node, if such a node exists, NULL otherwise
1727 
1728 --*/
1729 {
1730  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS SplayLinks;
1731  PEX_LOCK Lock = NULL, LastOverlapNode;
1732 
1733  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = NULL;
1734  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = FALSE;
1735 
1736  LastOverlapNode = NULL;
1737  SplayLinks = Tree;
1738 
1739  while (SplayLinks) {
1740 
1741  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, EX_LOCK, Links );
1742 
1743  //
1744  // We may have to go right in the tree if this lock covers a range before the start of this
1745  // range we are looking for overlap on or this lock is [0, 0). This is important since a lock
1746  // on [0, 0) will look like the extent is from [0, ~0], which is the only case where the zero
1747  // length lock relation of End < Start does not hold.
1748  //
1749 
1750  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart < (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart ||
1751  (Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == 0 && Lock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart == 0)) {
1752 
1753  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)EndingByte->QuadPart &&
1754  (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart) {
1755 
1756  //
1757  // The extent of the lock is less than the starting position of the
1758  // range we are checking and the lock is equal to the range, which
1759  // implies that the range and the lock are zero length.
1760  //
1761  // This is a zero length lock node and we are searching for zero
1762  // length overlap. Since the exclusive tree is one lock per node,
1763  // we are in the potential middle of a run of zero length locks in
1764  // the tree. Go left to find the first zero length lock.
1765  //
1766  // This is actually the same logic we'd use for equivalent locks,
1767  // but the only time that can happen in this tree is for zero length
1768  // locks.
1769  //
1770 
1771  LastOverlapNode = Lock;
1772 
1773  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = SplayLinks;
1774  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = FALSE;
1775 
1776  SplayLinks = RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks);
1777  continue;
1778  }
1779 
1780  //
1781  // This lock is strictly less than this byterange, so go
1782  // right in the tree.
1783  //
1784 
1785  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = SplayLinks;
1786  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = FALSE;
1787 
1788  SplayLinks = RtlRightChild(SplayLinks);
1789  continue;
1790  }
1791 
1792  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)EndingByte->QuadPart) {
1793 
1794  //
1795  // We have an overlap, but we need to see if the byterange starts
1796  // before this node so that there is the guarantee that we start
1797  // the search at the correct point. There may be still be predecessor
1798  // nodes covering the byterange.
1799  //
1800 
1801  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart) {
1802 
1803  //
1804  // This node begins at a byte offset prior to the byterange we
1805  // are checking, so it must be the correct starting position.
1806  //
1807 
1808  break;
1809  }
1810 
1811  //
1812  // Drop a marker at this node so that we can come back if it turns out
1813  // that the left subtree does not cover the range of bytes before this
1814  // node in the byterange.
1815  //
1816 
1817  LastOverlapNode = Lock;
1818  }
1819 
1820  //
1821  // It must now be the case this lock is strictly greater than the byterange,
1822  // or we have the candidate overlap case above, so go left in the tree.
1823  //
1824 
1825  if (LastEdgeNode) *LastEdgeNode = SplayLinks;
1826  if (GreaterThan) *GreaterThan = TRUE;
1827 
1828  SplayLinks = RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks);
1829  }
1830 
1831  if (SplayLinks == NULL) {
1832 
1833  //
1834  // We hit the edge of the tree. If the LastOverlapNode is set, it means that
1835  // we had kept searching left in the tree for a node that covered the starting
1836  // byte of the byterange, but didn't find it. If it isn't set, we'll do the
1837  // right thing anyway since Node <- NULL.
1838  //
1839 
1840  Lock = LastOverlapNode;
1841  }
1842 
1843  if (Lock == NULL) {
1844 
1845  //
1846  // No overlapping lock existed
1847  //
1848 
1849  return NULL;
1850  }
1851 
1852  //
1853  // Return the splay links of the first overlapping lock
1854  //
1855 
1856  return &Lock->Links;
1857 }

1860 PSH_LOCK
1861 FsRtlFindFirstOverlapInNode (
1862  IN PLOCKTREE_NODE Node,
1863  IN PLARGE_INTEGER StartingByte,
1864  IN PLARGE_INTEGER EndingByte
1865  )
1866 
1867 /*++
1868 
1869 Routine Description:
1870 
1871  This routine examines a shared lock node, usually a node which is known to be composed
1872  of several non-overlapping lock segments (holey), for true overlap with the indicated
1873  range. This is not handled in the normal overlap check (..FindFirstOverlappingSharedLock)
1874  since the needs for holey checks are rather different than the full node check.
1875 
1876 Arguments:
1877 
1878  Node - the lock tree node to be examined for overlap
1879 
1880  StartingByte - supplies the first byte offset of the range to check
1881 
1882  EndingByte - supplies the last byte offset of the range to check
1883 
1884 Return Value:
1885 
1886  PSH_LOCK - the first lock which overlaps with the specified range.
1887 
1888 --*/
1889 {
1890  PSH_LOCK Lock;
1891  PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY Link;
1892 
1893  for (Link = Node->Locks.Next;
1894  Link;
1895  Link = Link->Next) {
1896 
1897  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, SH_LOCK, Link );
1898 
1899  //
1900  // Logic is the same as above checkers. If the ending byte of the lock is less than the
1901  // starting byte of the range, OR we have the weird [0, 0) case, then the lock is almost
1902  // certainly less than the range.
1903  //
1904 
1905  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart < (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart ||
1906  (Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == 0 && Lock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart == 0)) {
1907 
1908  //
1909  // ... except if the lock and range are equivalent, in which case we have discovered
1910  // zero lock/range overlap.
1911  //
1912 
1913  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)EndingByte->QuadPart &&
1914  (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)StartingByte->QuadPart) {
1915 
1916  return Lock;
1917  }
1918 
1919  //
1920  // Look forward in the node.
1921  //
1922 
1923  continue;
1924  }
1925 
1926  //
1927  // No overlap at all if the lock begins at a higher byte than the last of the range.
1928  // We already covered zero length locks (where this is true, and overlap could still
1929  // occur).
1930  //
1931 
1932  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart > (ULONGLONG)EndingByte->QuadPart) {
1933 
1934  return NULL;
1935  }
1936 
1937  //
1938  // Regular overlap has occured. Return this lock.
1939  //
1940 
1941  return Lock;
1942  }
1943 
1944  //
1945  // If we invoke this check and wander off the end of the node without determining what is
1946  // going on, something is terribly wrong.
1947  //
1948 
1949  ASSERT( FALSE );
1950 
1951  return NULL;
1952 }

1955 PFILE_LOCK_INFO
1956 FsRtlGetNextFileLock (
1957  __in PFILE_LOCK FileLock,
1958  __in BOOLEAN Restart
1959  )
1960 
1961 /*++
1962 
1963 Routine Description:
1964 
1965  This routine enumerates the individual file locks denoted by the input file lock
1966  variable. It returns a pointer to the file lock information stored for each lock.
1967  The caller is responsible for synchronizing call to this procedure and for not
1968  altering any of the data returned by this procedure. If the caller does not
1969  synchronize the enumeration will not be reliably complete.
1970

1972  is as follows:
1973

1975  p != NULL;

1977

1979  }

1982

1984

1986  enumeration state is stored in the file lock variable so if multiple
1987  threads are enumerating the lock at the same time the results will
1988  be unpredictable.

1991  file lock tree or if we are continuing from a previous call.
1992 
1993 Return Value:
1994 
1995  PFILE_LOCK_INFO - Either it returns a pointer to the next file lock
1996  record for the input file lock or it returns NULL if there
1997  are not more locks.
1998

2301  Node = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links );
2302 
2303  Link = Node->Locks.Next;
2304  }
2305  }
2306 
2307  if (Link) {
2308 
2309  //
2310  // Found a Lock to return, copy it to the stack
2311  //
2312 
2313  ShLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, SH_LOCK, Link );
2314 
2315  FileLockInfo = ShLock->LockInfo;
2316  ContinuationPointer = ShLock;
2317  FoundReturnable = TRUE;
2318  }
2319 
2320  }
2321  }
2322 
2323  } else {
2324 
2325  //
2326  // Restarting the enumeration. Find leftmost node in the exclusive tree and hand back
2327  // the first lock, falling over to the shared if no exclusive locks are applied
2328  //
2329 
2330  if (LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree) {
2331 
2332  SplayLinks = LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree;
2333 
2334  while (RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks) != NULL) {
2335 
2336  SplayLinks = RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks);
2337  }
2338 
2339  ExLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, EX_LOCK, Links );
2340 
2341  FileLockInfo = ExLock->LockInfo;
2342  ContinuationPointer = ExLock;
2343  FoundReturnable = TRUE;
2344 
2345  } else {
2346 
2347  if (LockInfo->LockQueue.SharedLockTree) {
2348 
2349  SplayLinks = LockInfo->LockQueue.SharedLockTree;
2350 
2351  while (RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks) != NULL) {
2352 
2353  SplayLinks = RtlLeftChild(SplayLinks);
2354  }
2355 
2356  Node = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links );
2357  ShLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Node->Locks.Next, SH_LOCK, Link );
2358 
2359  FileLockInfo = ShLock->LockInfo;
2360  ContinuationPointer = ShLock;
2361  FoundReturnable = TRUE;
2362  }
2363  }
2364  }
2365 
2366  //
2367  // Release all the lock queues
2368  //
2369 
2370  FsRtlReleaseLockQueue (&LockInfo->LockQueue, OldIrql);
2371 
2372  if (!FoundReturnable) {
2373 
2374  //
2375  // No returnable lock was found, end of list
2376  //
2377 
2378  return NULL;
2379  }
2380 
2381  //
2382  // Update current enum location information
2383  //
2384 
2385  FileLock->LastReturnedLockInfo = FileLockInfo;
2386  FileLock->LastReturnedLock = ContinuationPointer;
2387 
2388  //
2389  // Return lock record to caller
2390  //
2391 
2392  return &FileLock->LastReturnedLockInfo;
2393 }

2396 BOOLEAN
2397 FsRtlCheckNoSharedConflict (
2398  IN PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue,
2399  IN PLARGE_INTEGER Starting,
2400  IN PLARGE_INTEGER Ending
2401  )
2402 /*++
2403 
2404 Routine Description:
2405 
2406  This routine checks to see if there is overlap in the shared locks with
2407  the given range. It is intended for use in the write access check path
2408  so that a rebalance will occur.
2409 
2410 Arguments:
2411 
2412  FileLock - Supplies the File Lock to check
2413 
2414  StartingByte - Supplies the first byte (zero based) to check
2415 
2416  Length - Supplies the length, in bytes, to check
2417 
2418  Key - Supplies the key to use in the check
2419 
2420  FileObject - Supplies the file object to use in the check
2421 
2422  ProcessId - Supplies the Process Id to use in the check
2423 
2424 Return Value:
2425 
2426  BOOLEAN - TRUE if the indicated user/request doesn't conflict in
2427  entire specified byte range, and FALSE otherwise
2428 
2429 --*/
2430 {
2431  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS SplayLinks, BeginLinks;
2432  PLOCKTREE_NODE Node;
2433 
2434  SplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingSharedNode( LockQueue->SharedLockTree,
2435  Starting,
2436  Ending,
2437  &BeginLinks,
2438  NULL);
2439 
2440  if (BeginLinks) {
2441 
2442  LockQueue->SharedLockTree = RtlSplay(BeginLinks);
2443  }
2444 
2445  //
2446  // If this node is holey, we'll have to walk the whole thing.
2447  //
2448 
2449  if (SplayLinks) {
2450 
2451  Node = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links );
2452 
2453  if (Node->HoleyNode) {
2454 
2455  return (BOOLEAN)(FsRtlFindFirstOverlapInNode( Node, Starting, Ending ) == NULL);
2456  }
2457 
2458  //
2459  // Overlapping non-holey node, so we do have shared lock conflict.
2460  //
2461 
2462  return FALSE;
2463  }
2464 
2465  //
2466  // No node overlaps.
2467  //
2468 
2469  return TRUE;
2470 }

2472 
2473 BOOLEAN
2474 FsRtlCheckNoExclusiveConflict (
2475  IN PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue,
2476  IN PLARGE_INTEGER Starting,
2477  IN PLARGE_INTEGER Ending,
2478  IN ULONG Key,
2479  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
2480  IN PVOID ProcessId
2481  )
2482 /*++
2483 
2484 Routine Description:
2485 
2486  This routine checks to see if there is conflict in the exclusive locks with
2487  a given range and identifying tuple of key, fileobject and process. This is
2488  for part of the read access path.
2489 
2490 Arguments:
2491 
2492  FileLock - Supplies the File Lock to check
2493 
2494  StartingByte - Supplies the first byte (zero based) to check
2495 
2496  Length - Supplies the length, in bytes, to check
2497 
2498  Key - Supplies the key to use in the check
2499 
2500  FileObject - Supplies the file object to use in the check
2501 
2502  ProcessId - Supplies the Process Id to use in the check
2503 
2504 Return Value:
2505 
2506  BOOLEAN - TRUE if the indicated user/request doesn't conflict in
2507  entire specified byte range, and FALSE otherwise
2508 
2509 --*/
2510 {
2511  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS SplayLinks, BeginLinks;
2512  PEX_LOCK Lock;
2513  BOOLEAN Status = TRUE;
2514 
2515  //
2516  // Find the node to begin the search at and go
2517  //
2518 
2519  for (SplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingExclusiveNode( LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree,
2520  Starting,
2521  Ending,
2522  &BeginLinks,
2523  NULL);
2524  SplayLinks;
2525  SplayLinks = RtlRealSuccessor(SplayLinks)) {
2526 
2527  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, EX_LOCK, Links );
2528 
2529  //
2530  // If the current lock is greater than the end of the range we're
2531  // looking for then the the user doesn't conflict
2532  //
2533  // if (Ending < Lock->StartingByte) ...
2534  //
2535 
2536  if ((ULONGLONG)Ending->QuadPart < (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart) {
2537 
2538  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckForExclusiveConflict, Ending < Lock->StartingByte\n", 0);
2539 
2540  break;
2541  }
2542 
2543  //
2544  // Check for any overlap with the request. The test for
2545  // overlap is that starting byte is less than or equal to the locks
2546  // ending byte, and the ending byte is greater than or equal to the
2547  // locks starting byte. We already tested for this latter case in
2548  // the preceding statement.
2549  //
2550  // if (Starting <= Lock->StartingByte + Lock->Length - 1) ...
2551  //
2552 
2553  if ((ULONGLONG)Starting->QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart) {
2554 
2555  //
2556  // This request overlaps the lock. We cannot grant the request
2557  // if the file object, process id, and key do not match. Otherwise
2558  // we'll continue looping looking at locks
2559  //
2560 
2561  if ((Lock->LockInfo.FileObject != FileObject) ||
2562  (Lock->LockInfo.ProcessId != ProcessId) ||
2563  (Lock->LockInfo.Key != Key)) {
2564 
2565  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckForExclusiveConflict, Range locked already\n", 0);
2566 
2567  Status = FALSE;
2568  break;
2569  }
2570  }
2571  }
2572 
2573  if (BeginLinks) {
2574 
2575  LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree = RtlSplay(BeginLinks);
2576  }
2577 
2578  //
2579  // We searched the entire range without a conflict so we'll note no conflict
2580  //
2581 
2582  return Status;
2583 }

2586 BOOLEAN
2587 FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead (
2588  __in PFILE_LOCK FileLock,
2589  __in PLARGE_INTEGER StartingByte,
2590  __in PLARGE_INTEGER Length,
2591  __in ULONG Key,
2592  __in PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
2593  __in PVOID ProcessId
2594  )
2595 
2596 /*++
2597 
2598 Routine Description:
2599 
2600  This routine checks to see if the caller has read access to the
2601  indicated range due to file locks.
2602 
2603 Arguments:
2604 
2605  FileLock - Supplies the File Lock to check
2606 
2607  StartingByte - Supplies the first byte (zero based) to check
2608 
2609  Length - Supplies the length, in bytes, to check
2610 
2611  Key - Supplies the to use in the check
2612 
2613  FileObject - Supplies the file object to use in the check
2614 
2615  ProcessId - Supplies the Process Id to use in the check
2616 
2617 Return Value:
2618 
2619  BOOLEAN - TRUE if the indicated user/request has read access to the
2620  entire specified byte range, and FALSE otherwise
2621 
2622 --*/
2623 
2624 {
2625  LARGE_INTEGER Starting;
2626  LARGE_INTEGER Ending;
2627 
2628  PLOCK_INFO LockInfo;
2629  PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue;
2630  KIRQL OldIrql;
2631  PFILE_LOCK_INFO LastLock;
2632  BOOLEAN Status;
2633 
2634  if ((LockInfo = (PLOCK_INFO) FileLock->LockInformation) == NULL) {
2635 
2636  //
2637  // No lock information on this FileLock
2638  //
2639 
2640  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead, No lock info\n", 0);
2641  return TRUE;
2642  }
2643 
2644  //
2645  // If there isn't an exclusive lock then we can immediately grant access
2646  //
2647 
2648  if (LockInfo->LockQueue.ExclusiveLockTree == NULL) {
2649  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead, No exlocks present\n", 0);
2650  return TRUE;
2651  }
2652 
2653  //
2654  // If length is zero then automatically give grant access
2655  //
2656 
2657  if ((ULONGLONG)Length->QuadPart == 0) {
2658 
2659  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead, Length == 0\n", 0);
2660  return TRUE;
2661  }
2662 
2663  //
2664  // Get our starting and ending byte position
2665  //
2666 
2667  Starting = *StartingByte;
2668  Ending.QuadPart = (ULONGLONG)Starting.QuadPart + (ULONGLONG)Length->QuadPart - 1;
2669 
2670  //
2671  // Now check lock queue
2672  //
2673 
2674  LockQueue = &LockInfo->LockQueue;
2675 
2676  //
2677  // Grab the waiting lock queue spinlock to exclude anyone from messing
2678  // with the queue while we're using it
2679  //
2680 
2681  FsRtlAcquireLockQueue(LockQueue, &OldIrql);
2682 
2683  //
2684  // If the range ends below the lowest existing lock, this read is OK.
2685  //
2686 
2687  if ( ((ULONGLONG)Ending.QuadPart < (ULONGLONG)LockInfo->LowestLockOffset) ) {
2688  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlFastCheckLockForRead (below lowest lock)\n", 0);
2689 
2690  FsRtlReleaseLockQueue(LockQueue, OldIrql);
2691  return TRUE;
2692  }
2693 
2694  //
2695  // If the caller just locked this range, he can read it.
2696  //
2697 
2698  LastLock = (PFILE_LOCK_INFO)FileObject->LastLock;
2699  if ((LastLock != NULL) &&
2700  ((ULONGLONG)Starting.QuadPart >= (ULONGLONG)LastLock->StartingByte.QuadPart) &&
2701  ((ULONGLONG)Ending.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)LastLock->EndingByte.QuadPart) &&
2702  (LastLock->Key == Key) &&
2703  (LastLock->ProcessId == ProcessId)) {
2704 
2705  FsRtlReleaseLockQueue(LockQueue, OldIrql);
2706  return TRUE;
2707  }
2708 
2709  //
2710  // Check the exclusive locks for a conflict. It is impossible to have
2711  // a read conflict with any shared lock.
2712  //
2713 
2714  Status = FsRtlCheckNoExclusiveConflict(LockQueue, &Starting, &Ending, Key, FileObject, ProcessId);
2715 
2716  FsRtlReleaseLockQueue(LockQueue, OldIrql);
2717 
2718  return Status;
2719 }

2868 
2869 VOID
2870 FsRtlSplitLocks (
2871  IN PLOCKTREE_NODE ParentNode,
2872  IN PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY *pStartLink,
2873  IN PLARGE_INTEGER LastShadowedByte,
2874  IN PLARGE_INTEGER GlueOffset
2875  )
2876 
2877 /*++
2878 
2879 Routine Description:
2880 
2881  This routine examines and possibly splits off shared locks associated
2882  with a node into new nodes of the lock tree. Called from routines that
2883  have just deleted locks.
2884 
2885  The arguments that supply the initial conditions for the operation are
2886  optional if the node is known to be holey.
2887 
2888 Arguments:
2889 
2890  ParentNode- Supplies the node the locks are coming from
2891 
2892  pStartLink - Supplies the pointer to the link address of the start of the
2893  range of locks in the ParentNode's locklist that need to be checked
2894 
2895  LastShadowedByte - Supplies the last byte offset that needs to be checked
2896 
2897  GlueOffset - Supplies the maximum offset affected by locks prior to this
2898  point in the list
2899 
2900 Return Value:
2901 
2902  BOOLEAN - True if the split was successful, False otherwise. The node will
2903  be marked as Holey if the split could not occur.
2904 
2905 --*/
2906 
2907 {
2908  PSH_LOCK Lock;
2909  PLOCKTREE_NODE NewNode;
2910  PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY Link, *pLink, *NextpLink;
2911  LARGE_INTEGER MaxOffset = {0}, StartOffset = {0}, HaltOffset;
2912 
2913  LOGICAL ExtentValid;
2914  LOGICAL FailedHoleySplit = FALSE;
2915 
2916  //
2917  // There are two cases: the node is holey or not. If the node is holey, at some
2918  // point we failed to get resources to complete a split, so despite our caller's
2919  // good intentions we need to go over the entire node.
2920  //
2921 
2922  if (ParentNode->HoleyNode) {
2923 
2924  //
2925  // Just move the starting link back to the front. The maximum offset and
2926  // starting offset of the node will be initialized in the loop. We also turn
2927  // off the holey flag, which will be turned on again as appropriate.
2928  //
2929 
2930  pStartLink = &ParentNode->Locks.Next;
2931  ParentNode->HoleyNode = FALSE;
2932 
2933  HaltOffset.QuadPart = ParentNode->Extent;
2934 
2935  } else {
2936 
2937  HaltOffset = *LastShadowedByte;
2938  MaxOffset = *GlueOffset;
2939  StartOffset.QuadPart = 0;
2940 
2941  if (!ParentNode->Locks.Next ||
2942  (ULONGLONG)HaltOffset.QuadPart <= (ULONGLONG)MaxOffset.QuadPart) {
2943 
2944  //
2945  // The parent node is not there, doesn't have links associated, or the
2946  // last possible byte that is affected by the operation our caller made
2947  // is interior to the max extent of all locks still in this node - in
2948  // which case there is nothing that needs to be done.
2949  //
2950 
2951  return;
2952  }
2953  }
2954 
2955  //
2956  // If the extent of the node is past the last byte affected by whatever
2957  // operations were done to this node, we can avoid the linear scan of
2958  // the list past that last affected byte since we already know the
2959  // extent of the entire list! If it is not (note that it would have to
2960  // be equal - by defintion) then we need to recalculate the extents of
2961  // all nodes we touch in this operation.
2962  //
2963 
2964  ExtentValid = (ParentNode->Extent > (ULONGLONG)HaltOffset.QuadPart);
2965 
2966  for (pLink = pStartLink;
2967  (Link = *pLink) != NULL;
2968  pLink = NextpLink) {
2969 
2970  NextpLink = &Link->Next;
2971 
2972  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, SH_LOCK, Link );
2973 
2974  if (ParentNode->Locks.Next == *pLink) {
2975 
2976  //
2977  // We're at the first lock in the node, and we know that we're going to leave
2978  // at least one lock here. Skip over that lock. We also know that the max
2979  // offset must be that locks's ending byte - make sure it is. Note that this
2980  // code is *exactly* the same as the update MaxOffset code at the bottom of
2981  // the loop.
2982  //
2983 
2984  MaxOffset.QuadPart = Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart;
2985 
2986  //
2987  // Set the starting offset of the node. This is only an issue for zero length
2988  // locks, so that we can figure out what is going on if we split a node and wind
2989  // up with some number of "overlapped" zero length locks at the front of the new
2990  // node. We must be able to notice this case, and not think that each needs to
2991  // be in a separate node.
2992  //
2993 
2994  StartOffset.QuadPart = Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart;
2995 
2996  //
2997  // If extents are invalid we also need to set it in case this turns out to
2998  // be the only lock at this node.
2999  //
3000 
3001  if (!ExtentValid) {
3002 
3003  ParentNode->Extent = (ULONGLONG)MaxOffset.QuadPart;
3004  }
3005 
3006  continue;
3007  }
3008 
3009  //
3010  // If the lock begins at a byte offset greater than the maximum offset seen to this
3011  // point, AND this is not a zero length node starting at the beginning of this node,
3012  // break the node. The second half of the test keeps co-incident zero length locks
3013  // in the same node. (zero length lock ---> starting = ending + 1).
3014  //
3015 
3016  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart > (ULONGLONG)MaxOffset.QuadPart &&
3017  !(Lock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart == 0 &&
3018  Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == StartOffset.QuadPart)) {
3019 
3020  //
3021  // Break the node up here
3022  //
3023 
3024  NewNode = FsRtlAllocateLockTreeNode();
3025 
3026  if (NewNode == NULL) {
3027 
3028  //
3029  // If we are out of resources, this node is now holey - we know that the locks at
3030  // this node do not completely cover the indicated range. Keep splitting for two
3031  // reasons: more resources may become available, and we must keep updating the
3032  // node's extent if it is known to be invalid.
3033  //
3034 
3035  //
3036  // Now if this node was already holey it is not possible to state that, if we
3037  // manage to split if further as we keep walking, that the resulting "left" node
3038  // is not holey. See below.
3039  //
3040 
3041  if (ParentNode->HoleyNode) {
3042 
3043  FailedHoleySplit = TRUE;
3044  }
3045 
3046  ParentNode->HoleyNode = TRUE;
3047 
3048  } else {

3052  //

3055  NewNode->HoleyNode = FALSE;
3056

3059  // a free right child, we use it, else find the successor node and use its
3060  // left child. One of these cases must be available since we know there are
3061  // no nodes between this node and its successor.
3062  //
3063 
3064  if (RtlRightChild(&ParentNode->Links) == NULL) {

3067 
3068  } else {

3072  }

3076  //

3086  //
3087

3092  // the maximum offset we have seen to this point.

3095  // is in the new node since if it was in the old node we wouldn't have been able to split.

3103  //

3107  ParentNode->HoleyNode = FALSE;
3108 
3109  } else {

3113  //
3114 
3115  FailedHoleySplit = FALSE;
3116  }
3117 
3118  //
3119  // Move over to the new node.
3120  //
3121 
3122  ParentNode = NewNode;
3123 
3124  continue;
3125  }
3126  }
3127 
3128  if (ExtentValid &&
3129  (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart > (ULONGLONG)HaltOffset.QuadPart) {
3130 
3131  //
3132  // Our extents are good and this lock is past the shadow, so we can stop
3133  //
3134 
3135  return;
3136  }
3137

3139 
3140  //

3142  //
3143 
3144  MaxOffset.QuadPart = Lock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart;
3145

3147

3150  //
3151

3159  // having been interior to GlueOffset)
3160  //
3161

4273 
4274  This routine fills in a new lock record of the appropriate type and inserts

4276 
4277 Arguments:

4280 
4281  FileObject - The associated file object to update hints in
4282 
4283  FileLockInfo - Supplies the new lock data to add to the lock queue

4348 
4349 //
4350 // Internal Support Routine
4351 //
4352 
4353 BOOLEAN
4354 FsRtlPrivateInsertSharedLock (
4355  IN PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue,
4356  IN PSH_LOCK NewLock
4357  )
4358 
4359 /*++
4360 
4361 Routine Description:
4362 
4363  This routine adds a new shared lock record to the File lock's current
4364  lock queue. Locks are inserted into nodes ordered by their starting byte.
4365 
4366 Arguments:
4367 
4368  LockQueue - Supplies the lock queue being modified
4369 
4370  NewLock - Supplies the new shared lock to add to the lock queue
4371 
4372 Return Value:
4373 
4374  BOOLEAN - True if the insert was successful, False if no resources were available
4375  to complete the operation.
4376 
4377 --*/
4378 {
4379  PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY pLink, Link;
4380  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS OverlappedSplayLinks, ParentSplayLinks;
4381  PLOCKTREE_NODE Node, NextNode;
4382  PSH_LOCK NextLock;
4383  BOOLEAN GreaterThan;
4384 
4385  OverlappedSplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingSharedNode( LockQueue->SharedLockTree,
4386  &NewLock->LockInfo.StartingByte,
4387  &NewLock->LockInfo.EndingByte,
4388  &ParentSplayLinks,
4389  &GreaterThan );
4390 
4391  if (OverlappedSplayLinks == NULL) {
4392 
4393  //
4394  // Simple insert case, build a new node
4395  //
4396 
4397  NextNode = FsRtlAllocateLockTreeNode();
4398 
4399  //
4400  // If no resources are available, simply fail now.
4401  //
4402 
4403  if (NextNode == NULL) {
4404 
4405  return FALSE;
4406  }
4407 
4408  RtlInitializeSplayLinks(&NextNode->Links);
4409  NextNode->HoleyNode = FALSE;
4410 
4411  NextNode->Locks.Next = NextNode->Tail.Next = &NewLock->Link;
4412  NextNode->Extent = (ULONGLONG)NewLock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart;
4413  NewLock->Link.Next = NULL;
4414 
4415  if (ParentSplayLinks) {
4416 
4417  //
4418  // We have a real parent node in the tree
4419  //
4420 
4421  if (GreaterThan) {
4422 
4423  ASSERT(RtlLeftChild(ParentSplayLinks) == NULL);
4424  RtlInsertAsLeftChild(ParentSplayLinks, &NextNode->Links);
4425 
4426  } else {
4427 
4428  ASSERT(RtlRightChild(ParentSplayLinks) == NULL);
4429  RtlInsertAsRightChild(ParentSplayLinks, &NextNode->Links);
4430  }
4431 
4432  //
4433  // Splay all new nodes in the tree
4434  //
4435 
4436  LockQueue->SharedLockTree = RtlSplay(&NextNode->Links);
4437 
4438  } else {
4439 
4440  //
4441  // First node in the tree
4442  //
4443 
4444  LockQueue->SharedLockTree = &NextNode->Links;
4445  }
4446 
4447  return TRUE;
4448  }
4449 
4450  //
4451  // Now we examine the node to see if it is holey as a result of a resource-failed split.
4452  // If it is, we must complete the split before adding the new lock.
4453  //
4454 
4455  Node = CONTAINING_RECORD( OverlappedSplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links );
4456 
4457  //
4458  // Search down the overlapped node finding the position for the new lock
4459  //
4460 
4461  for (pLink = &Node->Locks;
4462  (Link = pLink->Next) != NULL;
4463  pLink = Link) {
4464 
4465  PSH_LOCK Lock;
4466 
4467  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, SH_LOCK, Link );
4468 
4469  //
4470  // We sort locks on this list first by starting byte, then by whether the length is zero or not.
4471  // This is important so that zero length locks appear prior to non-zero length locks, so that
4472  // they are split out of nodes into the tree in the correct order.
4473  //
4474  // if (NewLock->StartingByte <= Lock->StartingByte) ...
4475  //
4476 
4477  if (((ULONGLONG)NewLock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart < (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart) ||
4478 
4479  ((ULONGLONG)NewLock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart == (ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart &&
4480  (NewLock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart == 0 || Lock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart != 0))) {
4481 
4482  break;
4483  }
4484  }
4485 
4486  //
4487  // At this point pLink points to the record that comes right after
4488  // the new lock that we're inserting so we can simply push the
4489  // newlock into the entrylist
4490  //
4491 
4492  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "InsertSharedLock, Insert Before = %08lx\n", Link);
4493 
4494  if (pLink->Next == NULL) {
4495 
4496  //
4497  // Adding onto the tail of the list
4498  //
4499 
4500  Node->Tail.Next = &NewLock->Link;
4501  }
4502 
4503  NewLock->Link.Next = pLink->Next;
4504  pLink->Next = &NewLock->Link;
4505 
4506  //
4507  // And splay the node we inserted into
4508  //
4509 
4510  LockQueue->SharedLockTree = RtlSplay(OverlappedSplayLinks);
4511 
4512  if ((ULONGLONG)NewLock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart > Node->Extent) {
4513 
4514  //
4515  // The new lock extends the range of this node, so fix up the extent
4516  //
4517 
4518  Node->Extent = NewLock->LockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart;
4519 
4520  //
4521  // Walk across the remainder of the tree integrating newly overlapping
4522  // nodes into the node we just inserted the new lock into. Note that
4523  // this isn't so much a walk as a repeated examination of our successor's
4524  // until one does not overlap (or we hit the end).
4525  //
4526 
4527  ParentSplayLinks = OverlappedSplayLinks;
4528 
4529  for (OverlappedSplayLinks = RtlRealSuccessor(ParentSplayLinks);
4530  OverlappedSplayLinks;
4531  OverlappedSplayLinks = RtlRealSuccessor(ParentSplayLinks)) {
4532 
4533  NextNode = CONTAINING_RECORD( OverlappedSplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links );
4534  NextLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( NextNode->Locks.Next, SH_LOCK, Link );
4535 
4536  if ((ULONGLONG)NextLock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart > Node->Extent) {
4537 
4538  //
4539  // This node is not overlapped, so stop
4540  //
4541 
4542  break;
4543  }
4544 
4545  //
4546  // If we are integrating a holey node into a non-holey node, try to split
4547  // the node first. It will be better to get this done with a smaller node
4548  // than a big, fully integrated one. Note that we are guaranteed that the
4549  // node will remain a candidate for integration since the first lock on the
4550  // node will still be there, and overlaps.
4551  //
4552 
4553  if (!Node->HoleyNode && NextNode->HoleyNode) {
4554 
4555  FsRtlSplitLocks( NextNode, NULL, NULL, NULL );
4556  }
4557 
4558  //
4559  // Integrate the locks in this node into our list
4560  //
4561 
4562  Node->Tail.Next->Next = NextNode->Locks.Next;
4563  Node->Tail.Next = NextNode->Tail.Next;
4564 
4565  if (NextNode->Extent > Node->Extent) {
4566 
4567  //
4568  // If the node we just swallowed was (still!) holey, we perhaps made this
4569  // node holey too. The resolution of this is left to the lock split we will
4570  // perform after integration is complete.
4571  //
4572  // Note that if the extent of the node we are swallowing is interior
4573  // to the current node, we just covered whatever holes it contained.
4574  //
4575 
4576  if (NextNode->HoleyNode) {
4577 
4578  Node->HoleyNode = TRUE;
4579  }
4580 
4581  Node->Extent = NextNode->Extent;
4582  }
4583 
4584  //
4585  // Free the now empty node.
4586  //
4587 
4588  RtlDeleteNoSplay( OverlappedSplayLinks, &LockQueue->SharedLockTree );
4589  FsRtlFreeLockTreeNode( NextNode );
4590  }
4591  }
4592 
4593  //
4594  // Now, perhaps this node is still holey. For grins lets try one more time to split
4595  // this thing apart.
4596  //
4597 
4598  if (Node->HoleyNode) {
4599 
4600  FsRtlSplitLocks( Node, NULL, NULL, NULL );
4601  }
4602 
4603  //
4604  // And return to our caller
4605  //
4606 
4607  return TRUE;
4608 }

4627 
4628 Arguments:
4629 
4630  LockQueue - Supplies the lock queue being modified
4631 
4632  NewLock - Supplies the new exclusive lock to add to the lock queue
4633 
4634 Return Value:
4635 
4636  None.
4637 
4638 --*/
4639 
4640 {
4641  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS OverlappedSplayLinks, ParentSplayLinks;
4642  BOOLEAN GreaterThan;
4643 
4644  OverlappedSplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingExclusiveNode( LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree,
4645  &NewLock->LockInfo.StartingByte,
4646  &NewLock->LockInfo.EndingByte,
4647  &ParentSplayLinks,
4648  &GreaterThan );
4649 
4650  //
4651  // This is the exclusive tree. Nothing can overlap (caller is supposed to ensure this) unless
4652  // the lock is a zero length lock, in which case we just insert it - still.
4653  //
4654 
4655  ASSERT(!OverlappedSplayLinks || NewLock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart == 0);
4656 
4657  //
4658  // Simple insert ...
4659  //
4660 
4661  RtlInitializeSplayLinks(&NewLock->Links);
4662 
4663  if (OverlappedSplayLinks) {
4664 
4665  //
4666  // With zero length locks we have OverlappedSplayLinks at the starting point
4667  // of a run of zero length locks, so we have to e flexible about where the new
4668  // node is inserted.
4669  //
4670 
4671  if (RtlRightChild(OverlappedSplayLinks)) {
4672 
4673  //
4674  // Right slot taken. We can use the left slot or go to the successor's left slot
4675  //
4676 
4677  if (RtlLeftChild(OverlappedSplayLinks)) {
4678 
4679  ASSERT(RtlLeftChild(RtlRealSuccessor(OverlappedSplayLinks)) == NULL);
4680  RtlInsertAsLeftChild(RtlRealSuccessor(OverlappedSplayLinks), &NewLock->Links);
4681 
4682  } else {
4683 
4684  RtlInsertAsLeftChild(OverlappedSplayLinks, &NewLock->Links);
4685  }
4686 
4687 
4688  } else {
4689 
4690  RtlInsertAsRightChild(OverlappedSplayLinks, &NewLock->Links);
4691  }
4692 
4693  } else if (ParentSplayLinks) {
4694 
4695  //
4696  // We have a real parent node in the tree, and must be at a leaf since
4697  // there was no overlap
4698  //
4699 
4700  if (GreaterThan) {
4701 
4702  ASSERT(RtlLeftChild(ParentSplayLinks) == NULL);
4703  RtlInsertAsLeftChild(ParentSplayLinks, &NewLock->Links);
4704 
4705  } else {
4706 
4707  ASSERT(RtlRightChild(ParentSplayLinks) == NULL);
4708  RtlInsertAsRightChild(ParentSplayLinks, &NewLock->Links);
4709  }
4710 
4711  } else {
4712 
4713  //
4714  // First node in the tree
4715  //
4716 
4717  LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree = &NewLock->Links;
4718  }
4719 
4720  //
4721  // And return to our caller
4722  //
4723 
4724  return;
4725 }

4729 // Internal Support Routine
4730 //
4731 
4732 VOID
4733 FsRtlPrivateCheckWaitingLocks (
4734  IN PLOCK_INFO LockInfo,
4735  IN PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue,
4736  IN KIRQL OldIrql
4737  )
4738 
4739 /*++
4740 
4741 Routine Description:
4742 
4743  This routine checks to see if any of the current waiting locks are now
4744  be satisfied, and if so it completes their IRPs.
4745 
4746 Arguments:
4747 
4748  LockInfo - LockInfo which LockQueue is member of
4749 
4750  LockQueue - Supplies queue which needs to be checked
4751 
4752  OldIrql - Irql to restore when LockQueue is released
4753 
4754 Return Value:
4755 
4756  None.
4757 
4758 --*/
4759 
4760 {
4761  PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY *pLink, Link;
4762  NTSTATUS NewStatus;
4763  BOOLEAN Result;
4764 
4765  pLink = &LockQueue->WaitingLocks.Next;
4766  while ((Link = *pLink) != NULL) {
4767 
4768  PWAITING_LOCK WaitingLock;
4769 
4770  PIRP Irp;
4771  PIO_STACK_LOCATION IrpSp;
4772 
4773  BOOLEAN AccessGranted;
4774 
4775  FILE_LOCK_INFO FileLockInfo;
4776 
4777  //
4778  // Get a pointer to the waiting lock record
4779  //
4780 
4781  WaitingLock = CONTAINING_RECORD( Link, WAITING_LOCK, Link );
4782 
4783  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckWaitingLocks, Loop top, WaitingLock = %08lx\n", WaitingLock);
4784 
4785  //
4786  // Get a local copy of the necessary fields we'll need to use
4787  //
4788 
4789  Irp = WaitingLock->Irp;
4790  IrpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( Irp );
4791 
4792  FileLockInfo.StartingByte = IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.ByteOffset;
4793  FileLockInfo.Length = *IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Length;
4794  FileLockInfo.EndingByte.QuadPart =
4795  (ULONGLONG)FileLockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart + (ULONGLONG)FileLockInfo.Length.QuadPart - 1;
4796 
4797  FileLockInfo.FileObject = IrpSp->FileObject;
4798  FileLockInfo.ProcessId = IoGetRequestorProcess( Irp );
4799  FileLockInfo.Key = IrpSp->Parameters.LockControl.Key;
4800  FileLockInfo.ExclusiveLock = BooleanFlagOn(IrpSp->Flags, SL_EXCLUSIVE_LOCK);
4801 
4802  //
4803  // Now case on whether we're trying to take out an exclusive lock or
4804  // a shared lock. And in both cases try to get the appropriate access
4805  // For the exclusive case we send in a NULL file object and process
4806  // id, this will ensure that the lookup does not give us write
4807  // access through an exclusive lock.
4808  //
4809 
4810  if (FileLockInfo.ExclusiveLock) {
4811 
4812  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckWaitingLocks do we have write access?\n", 0);
4813 
4814  AccessGranted = FsRtlPrivateCheckForExclusiveLockAccess(
4815  LockQueue,
4816  &FileLockInfo );
4817  } else {
4818 
4819  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckWaitingLocks do we have read access?\n", 0);
4820 
4821  AccessGranted = FsRtlPrivateCheckForSharedLockAccess(
4822  LockQueue,
4823  &FileLockInfo );
4824 
4825  }
4826 
4827  //
4828  // Now AccessGranted tells us whether we can really get the access for
4829  // the range we want.
4830  //
4831  // No matter what happens, this Irp must be completed now - even if we
4832  // are resource starved. User mode deadlock could be induced since there
4833  // may no longer be a pending unlock to cause a rescan of the waiting
4834  // list.
4835  //
4836 
4837  if (AccessGranted) {
4838 
4839  DebugTrace(0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckWaitingLocks now has access\n", 0);
4840 
4841  //
4842  // Clear the cancel routine
4843  //
4844 
4845  IoAcquireCancelSpinLock( &Irp->CancelIrql );
4846  IoSetCancelRoutine( Irp, NULL );
4847 
4848  //
4849  // If the IRP got itself cancelled, it is cancelled and we won't grant it.
4850  // The canceller is waiting for the queue spinlock right now.
4851  //
4852 
4853  if (Irp->Cancel) {
4854 
4855  AccessGranted = FALSE;
4856  }
4857 
4858  IoReleaseCancelSpinLock( Irp->CancelIrql );
4859 
4860  if (AccessGranted) {
4861 
4862  Result = FsRtlPrivateInsertLock( LockInfo, IrpSp->FileObject, &FileLockInfo );
4863 
4864  //
4865  // Now we need to remove this granted waiter and complete
4866  // it's irp.
4867  //
4868 
4869  *pLink = Link->Next;
4870  if (Link == LockQueue->WaitingLocksTail.Next) {
4871  LockQueue->WaitingLocksTail.Next = (PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY) pLink;
4872  }
4873 
4874  //
4875  // Release LockQueue and complete this waiter
4876  //
4877 
4878  FsRtlReleaseLockQueue( LockQueue, OldIrql );
4879 
4880  //
4881  // Reference the fileobject over the completion attempt so we can have a
4882  // chance to cleanup safely if we fail
4883  //
4884 
4885  ObReferenceObject( FileLockInfo.FileObject );
4886 
4887  //
4888  // Now we can complete the IRP, if we don't get back success
4889  // from the completion routine then we remove the lock we just
4890  // inserted.
4891  //
4892 
4893  FsRtlCompleteLockIrp( LockInfo,
4894  WaitingLock->Context,
4895  Irp,
4896  (Result? STATUS_SUCCESS : STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES),
4897  &NewStatus,
4898  FileLockInfo.FileObject );
4899 
4900  if (Result && !NT_SUCCESS(NewStatus)) {
4901 
4902  //
4903  // Irp was not successful, remove lock if it was added.
4904  //
4905 
4906  FsRtlPrivateRemoveLock (
4907  LockInfo,
4908  &FileLockInfo,
4909  FALSE );
4910  }
4911 
4912  //
4913  // Drop our private reference to the fileobject
4914  //
4915 
4916  ObDereferenceObject( FileLockInfo.FileObject );
4917 
4918  //
4919  // Re-acquire queue lock
4920  //
4921 
4922  FsRtlAcquireLockQueue( LockQueue, &OldIrql );
4923 
4924  //
4925  // Start scan over from beginning
4926  //
4927 
4928  pLink = &LockQueue->WaitingLocks.Next;
4929 
4930 
4931  //
4932  // Free up pool
4933  //
4934 
4935  FsRtlFreeWaitingLock( WaitingLock );
4936 
4937  continue;
4938  }
4939  }
4940 
4941  DebugTrace( 0, Dbg, "FsRtlCheckWaitingLocks still no access\n", 0);
4942 
4943  //
4944  // Move to next lock
4945  //
4946 
4947  pLink = &Link->Next;
4948  }
4949 
4950  //
4951  // And return to our caller
4952  //
4953 
4954  return;
4955 }

4958 BOOLEAN
4959 FsRtlPrivateCheckForExclusiveLockAccess (
4960  IN PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue,
4961  IN PFILE_LOCK_INFO FileLockInfo
4962  )
4963 /*++
4964 
4965 Routine Description:
4966 
4967  This routine checks to see if the caller can get an exclusive lock on
4968  the indicated range due to file locks in the passed in lock queue.
4969 
4970  Assumes Lock queue is held by caller
4971 
4972 Arguments:
4973 
4974  LockQueue - Queue which needs to be checked for collision
4975 
4976  FileLockInfo - Lock which is being checked
4977 
4978 
4979 Return Value:
4980 
4981  BOOLEAN - TRUE if the indicated user can place the exclusive lock over the
4982  entire specified byte range, and FALSE otherwise
4983 
4984 --*/
4985 
4986 {
4987  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS SplayLinks, LastSplayLinks = NULL;
4988  PLOCKTREE_NODE Node;
4989  PSH_LOCK ShLock;
4990  PEX_LOCK ExLock;
4991 
4992  if (LockQueue->SharedLockTree &&
4993  (SplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingSharedNode( LockQueue->SharedLockTree,
4994  &FileLockInfo->StartingByte,
4995  &FileLockInfo->EndingByte,
4996  &LastSplayLinks, NULL))) {
4997 
4998  Node = CONTAINING_RECORD(SplayLinks, LOCKTREE_NODE, Links);
4999 
5000  //
5001  // If this node is holey, we'll have to walk the whole thing.
5002  //
5003 
5004  if (Node->HoleyNode) {
5005 
5006  ShLock = FsRtlFindFirstOverlapInNode( Node,
5007  &FileLockInfo->StartingByte,
5008  &FileLockInfo->EndingByte );
5009 
5010  } else {
5011 
5012  ShLock = CONTAINING_RECORD(Node->Locks.Next, SH_LOCK, Link);
5013  }
5014 
5015  //
5016  // Look for overlap that we care about. Perhaps no overlap existed in the holey case.
5017  //
5018 
5019  if (ShLock &&
5020  (FileLockInfo->Length.QuadPart || ShLock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart)) {
5021 
5022  //
5023  // If we are checking a nonzero extent and overlapped, it is fatal. If we
5024  // are checking a zero extent and overlapped a nonzero extent, it is fatal.
5025  //
5026 
5027  return FALSE;
5028  }
5029  }
5030 
5031  if (LastSplayLinks) {
5032 
5033  LockQueue->SharedLockTree = RtlSplay(LastSplayLinks);
5034  LastSplayLinks = NULL;
5035  }
5036 
5037  if (LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree &&
5038  (SplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingExclusiveNode( LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree,
5039  &FileLockInfo->StartingByte,
5040  &FileLockInfo->EndingByte,
5041  &LastSplayLinks, NULL))) {
5042 
5043  ExLock = CONTAINING_RECORD(SplayLinks, EX_LOCK, Links);
5044 
5045  if (FileLockInfo->Length.QuadPart || ExLock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart) {
5046 
5047  //
5048  // If we are checking a nonzero extent and overlapped, it is fatal. If we
5049  // are checking a zero extent and overlapped a nonzero extent, it is fatal.
5050  //
5051 
5052  return FALSE;
5053  }
5054  }
5055 
5056  if (LastSplayLinks) {
5057 
5058  LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree = RtlSplay(LastSplayLinks);
5059  }
5060 
5061  //
5062  // We searched the entire range without a conflict so we can grant
5063  // the exclusive lock
5064  //
5065 
5066  return TRUE;
5067 }

5070 BOOLEAN
5071 FsRtlPrivateCheckForSharedLockAccess (
5072  IN PLOCK_QUEUE LockQueue,
5073  IN PFILE_LOCK_INFO FileLockInfo
5074  )
5075 /*++
5076 
5077 Routine Description:
5078 
5079  This routine checks to see if the caller can get a shared lock on
5080  the indicated range due to file locks in the passed in lock queue.
5081 
5082  Assumes Lock queue is held by caller
5083 
5084 Arguments:
5085 
5086  LockQueue - Queue which needs to be checked for collision
5087 
5088  FileLockInfo - Lock which is being checked
5089 
5090 Arguments:
5091 
5092 Return Value:
5093 
5094  BOOLEAN - TRUE if the indicated user can place the shared lock over
5095  entire specified byte range, and FALSE otherwise
5096 
5097 --*/
5098 
5099 {
5100  PEX_LOCK Lock;
5101  PRTL_SPLAY_LINKS SplayLinks, LastSplayLinks;
5102  BOOLEAN Status = TRUE;
5103 
5104  //
5105  // If there are no exclusive locks, this is quick ...
5106  //
5107 
5108  if (LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree == NULL) {
5109 
5110  return TRUE;
5111  }
5112 
5113  //
5114  // No lock in the shared lock tree can prevent access, so just search the exclusive
5115  // tree for conflict.
5116  //
5117 
5118  for (SplayLinks = FsRtlFindFirstOverlappingExclusiveNode( LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree,
5119  &FileLockInfo->StartingByte,
5120  &FileLockInfo->EndingByte,
5121  &LastSplayLinks, NULL);
5122  SplayLinks;
5123  SplayLinks = RtlRealSuccessor(SplayLinks)) {
5124 
5125  Lock = CONTAINING_RECORD( SplayLinks, EX_LOCK, Links );
5126 
5127  if ((ULONGLONG)Lock->LockInfo.StartingByte.QuadPart > (ULONGLONG)FileLockInfo->EndingByte.QuadPart) {
5128 
5129  //
5130  // This node is covering a range greater than the range we care about,
5131  // so we're done
5132  //
5133 
5134  break;
5135  }
5136 
5137  //
5138  // We may not be able to grant the request if the fileobject, processid,
5139  // and key do not match.
5140  //
5141 
5142  if ((Lock->LockInfo.FileObject != FileLockInfo->FileObject) ||
5143  (Lock->LockInfo.ProcessId != FileLockInfo->ProcessId) ||
5144  (Lock->LockInfo.Key != FileLockInfo->Key)) {
5145 
5146  //
5147  // We have a mismatch between caller and owner. It is ok not to conflict
5148  // if the caller and owner will have/have zero length locks (zero length
5149  // locks cannot conflict).
5150  //
5151 
5152  if (FileLockInfo->Length.QuadPart || Lock->LockInfo.Length.QuadPart) {
5153 
5154  Status = FALSE;
5155  break;
5156  }
5157  }
5158  }
5159 
5160  if (LastSplayLinks) {
5161 
5162  LockQueue->ExclusiveLockTree = RtlSplay(LastSplayLinks);
5163  }
5164 
5165  //
5166  // We searched the entire range without a conflict so we can grant
5167  // the shared lock
5168  //
5169 
5170  return Status;
5171 }
